	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_603438">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_603438"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Istari</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
presence of mind is just plain better than combustion for dealing damage, if not efficiency. combust doubles spell damage every 5 minutes, and presence gives you a free spell every 3 minutes. each does the same bonus basically, but pom gives it nearly twice as fast.<br /></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
That's not true. PoM just makes your next spell instant -- it provides no damage bonus or mana savings at all. It's not the same bonus as Combustion, since Combustion is designed to peak dps and efficiency. Remember that Combustion also kicks in Ignite, which makes it even more efficient. Along the way to Combustion, you also must get Fire Power, which further increases dps and efficiency. It's tough to compare one spell vs another in isolation because the talent tree builds talents upon one another.<br />
<br />
We're lucky as mages that we have three different viable ways to go:<br />
<br />
1. Fire spec mages sacrifice crowd control and instant spell availability for raw dps and efficiency.<br />
<br />
2. Arcane mages sacrifice crowd control and raw dps/efficiency for instant spell availability.<br />
<br />
3. Frost mages sacrifice raw dps/efficiency and instant spell availability for crowd control.<br />
<br />
Now these are generalizations, and there are individual spells that are exceptions, but the way the talent tree is built, spells build on each other, so that moving down one discipline gives you layers of benefits that more than outweigh any one spell or talent in another school. <br />
<br />
I see talent trees from other classes and hear a lot of &quot;oh, this tree is pretty worthless&quot;, or &quot;there's not a lot in this tree I want&quot;. For mages, you never hear that, since you can go any of the three directions and have a competent mage.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		
<img class="inlineimg" src="images/legacy_images/statusicon/user_online.gif" alt="Pyre is online now" border="0" />

		
		
		
		&nbsp;
