	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_603593">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_603593"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>Istari</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Calculations on arcane meditation bizarrely come out quite favorable compared to + mana (I have a massive and poorly written psuedoproof if anyone wants to see it).</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>After really looking at the talent, I'm finding that Arcane Meditation should be more useful than I first expected, but still is a very difficult thing to justify for most people.<br />
<br />
At first glance Arcane Meditation appears to be fairly useless.  15% of your regen during combat?  If you have 300 spirit (around 85-90 mana regen per tick) that'll amount to recovering about 13 mana per tick while casting.  Pretty weak.<br />
<br />
But that's not really a useful way to view the ability.  Its regen active only during casting, right?  So wouldn't it make more sense to subtract that regenned mana from the cost of your spells, to get a number that we can use to compare its efficiency benefit to + %damage and - %mana cost abilities?<br />
<br />
First I'll open with an assumption: that the Arcane Medition effect will continue during the &quot;down time&quot; between when a spell completes casting and when normal spirit regen would kick in.  The description doesn't guarantee this - can anybody confirm?<br />
<br />
Now, let's look at your level 60 fireball, which takes 3 seconds to cast.  That's 1.5 ticks, so we'll say you regain an average of 20 mana due to maxed Arcane Meditation with 300 spirit during that cast time.  That's a bit over 5% mana cost reduction.  5 points for a 5% reduction in mana cost?  Well, that's not so hot - consider Frost Channeling, which grants a 5% reduction in mana cost for each point placed into it, or Arcane Mind which grants you a raw 2% more mana per point.<br />
<br />
If you're casting a *single* fireball, and if Arcane Meditation functions during the 5 second cooldown from when a spell completes to when spirit picks back up, then you have a full 8 seconds where you'll get the partial effect.  Now you'd be talking about 50 mana regenned, give or take - that's almost 13% increase in efficiency in that instance.  Starting to look a little better in that case.<br />
<br />
So, we'll say that maxed Arcane Meditation with 300 Spirit makes your Fireball anywhere from 5% to 13% more efficient when cast below full mana, depending on how long you wait between casts (and assuming that Arcane Meditation works in the dead time waiting for spirit regen to kick in).<br />
<br />
Now, say you're relying on something like Scorch instead.  150 mana with a 1.5 second cast, and you'll regen about 3/4 a tick's worth per cast: 9.75 mana per cast when chaincasting.  That's a 6.5% increase in efficiency, which is again not so hot.   However, for a single Scorch not being chaincast, it jumps way up to a regen of 42.25 mana, which is a whopping 28% reduction in cost as opposed to if you did that without the ability (but really, is that something you'd ever do?)<br />
<br />
Now, the wildcard here is that all of these numbers are done assuming 300 spirit!  The chances are, you don't have that.  But at some point you might, and you may have even more than that... Arcane Meditation is one of the few mage talents whose effect is enhanced by gear.<br />
<br />
Of course, you also have the special cases of instants (which gain nothing) and casting when starting out at full mana (also gaining nothing).<br />
<br />
So my conclusion is &quot;not as useless as I expected, but still not so hot.&quot;  Normal spirit regen just isn't good enough to justify spending 5 points to get 15% of it working for you while casting.  This was a good idea for an ability, but they got the magnitude of the effect wrong - bump it up to 10% per point, and you start to look at something worth getting.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
